  "prompt": "Is mercury a radioactive element?",
  "response": "Mercury is not a radioactive element. It is a heavy metal that exists in several forms, including elemental mercury (Hg), inorganic mercury compounds, and organic mercury compounds. Mercury is stable and does not undergo radioactive decay naturally.\n\nHowever, there are radioactive isotopes of mercury, such as mercury-203 (^203Hg) and mercury-197 (^197Hg), which are artificially produced through nuclear reactions and do emit radiation. These isotopes are not found naturally in significant quantities and are typically used in scientific research and medical applications.\n\nIn summary, naturally occurring mercury is not radioactive, but certain isotopes of mercury can be radioactive when created artificially.",
